<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/014788bfe3694be2a1ba41180c8ac836> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "<STRONG>Contact and Change</STRONG><BR>\nThe Indonesian provinces of Papua and West Papua occupy the western half of the island of New Guinea. The eastern half is the independent state of Papua New Guinea. When it was a Dutch colony, the western half of New Guinea was part of the Netherlands East Indies. After the Second World War, Indonesia gained independence. Meanwhile, New Guinea remained under Dutch rule. It was known then as Netherlands New Guinea. In 1962, sovereignty passed to Indonesia, and the name was changed several times (Irian Barat, Irian Jaya). Since 2001, this western section has been known as Papua. In 2008, it was divided in two provinces: Papua and West Papua (Papua Barat).<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>First contacts</STRONG><BR>\nFollowing a superficial charting of the coast, the Netherlands laid claim to the territory in 1846. It was not until late in the 19th century that the Dutch began to focus more closely on New Guinea. Dutch colonial troops, fighting in the East Indies army (KNIL), were given a new assignment by Batavia’s governor general: to explore and map Netherlands New Guinea. Between 1907 and 1915, they recorded their experiences in articles, maps and photos. These Dutch soldiers had encountered indigenous Papuans whose existence had until then been unknown. The objects they collected would later be acquired by Dutch ethnographic museums. It was around this time that the main cities on the coast were founded: Jayapura, Fakfak, Merauke and Manokwari.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Expeditions</STRONG><BR>\nEarly in the 20th century, scientific institutions began organising expeditions into the interior of New Guinea. Many had as their objective to reach the permanently snow-capped mountains that ranged from east to west in the centre of the island. The first Dutchmen to walk in the snows of New Guinea did so in 1909. The last of these Dutch expeditions, to the Star Mountains, went in 1959. The objects acquired on these expeditions eventually came into the collections of the Tropenmuseum and other ethnographic museums in the Netherlands.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Missionaries</STRONG><BR>\nProtestant missionaries had begun to spread Christianity among the Papuans in the 19th century. Catholic missionaries did not arrive until after 1900. Protestants set up missions in the north and Catholics in the south; reflecting the division in the Netherlands. In the central highlands, both Catholic and Protestant missionaries were active. Missionaries from other European countries also came to spread the Gospel in New Guinea. Today, most Christian Papuans in the north are Protestant, and in the south Catholic. Over three-quarters of the Papuan population of the Indonesian half of New Guinea is now Christian.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Dutch rule</STRONG><BR>\nAfter the Second World War, the Dutch administration began stimulating agriculture, education and healthcare. The administration was led by a governor in Hollandia (later Jayapura). The population registry in Hollandia organised censuses and encouraged anthropological and linguistic research. New collections of ethnographic material were sent to Dutch museums in Leiden, Amsterdam and Rotterdam. When sovereignty over Netherlands New Guinea passed to Indonesia in 1962, Dutch rule came to an end."^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
