<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/0b616f5161da4d56a184fac5c778eff3> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "<STRONG>Religions such as Vodou on Haiti, Santería on Cuba, Winti in Suriname and Umbanda or Candomblé in Brazil emerged in the colonial period. They still attract large numbers of adherents. A key aspect of these religions is the possession by a god or spirit of a worshipper during a ceremony. The possessed go into a trance and the way they behave reveals the identity of the god or spirit that controls them. Others at the ceremony can then ask them for help and advice on all kinds of matters.</STRONG><br>\n<br>\n<STRONG>Mixture</STRONG><br>\nChristian plantation-owners saw the religious traditions and ideas of the Africans as heathen worship and tried to forbid it. Despite the ban, the religion continued in secret. New mixed forms of religious practice developed, since Christian forms of worship were tolerated. In this hybrid religion, Christian saints embodied the essence of African gods. <br>\n<br>\n<STRONG>Iemanjá and Maria</STRONG><br>\nChristian saints worshipped by the plantation-owners in their churches and chapels with a similar form, colour, property or attribute were adopted by the Africans to represent their African gods and spirits. For example, the image of the Virgin Mary, who is often shown in a light-blue garment, resembles the West African water goddess Iemanjá. So statues of the Virgin became Iemanjá, disguised as Maria.<br>\n<br>\n<STRONG>Dance festivals</STRONG><br>\nEnslaves Africans on plantation were occasionally allowed to organise dance festivals. These developed into religious gatherings. By using Christian forms and symbols, they were able to conceal their own religious practices from the planters. At the same time, while preserving their religious rituals, the Africans managed in this way to maintain their knowledge of traditional herbal medicine and cures as well as elements of their languages."^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
