<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/12d36084f5f64a64b3949082e43f2b2c> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "In North and South America, the main use of slave labour was on plantations. These were large agricultural estates in which a single crop was cultivated: coffee, cotton and in Suriname mainly sugar. Europeans were in charge on the plantations. African slaves did the heavy work. Plantations were like villages. The planter or manager would live in a large house. There were factories and sheds, and buildings in which the slaves lived. Slaves cultivated their own crops on small patches of ground, and some also kept hens. Beyond this lay the fields in which crops were grown for export, as well as food for the Europeans.<br>\n<br>\nSuriname<br>\nSuriname was a true plantation economy. Around 1750, there were about 450 plantations on which over 60,000 Africans were forced to work. Surinamese estates ranged from 200 to over 1,000 hectares. The slaves were kept under control by the harsh violence of a few thousand well-armed Europeans. In Suriname, the death rate among slaves was higher than the birth rate. Few slaves on the plantations lived past the age of 36.<br>\n<br>\nAntilles<br>\nThe Antilles were above all trading colonies in which the produce of the Caribbean, Latin America and North America was bought and sold. Because of the dry climate, the plantations on Curaçao were less suited to the typical export crops of sugar and coffee. Food and livestock were the main products of these plantations. The slaves worked in far better conditions here than in Suriname. The death rate was therefore lower among slaves on the Antilles."^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
