<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/2285f8d916804a38aafd94b99e8b1045> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "<STRONG>Dance and Ritual</STRONG><BR>\nEveryday life in New Guinea is frequently interrupted for rituals. Some may mark significant moments in an individual’s life, other feasts may involve the entire village. Examples include initiation rites in which boys become men, and creation ceremonies in which the balance of village life is restored. Music and dance are always key elements in these rituals.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Initiation</STRONG><BR>\nThere are all kinds of initiation rites in New Guinea. Yet they all have elements in common. In the end, it comes down to a ritual in which boys are separated from their mothers and weaned from their carefree childhood years. It is a preparation for the social responsibilities of an adult man. Part of the ritual involves the boys being kept isolated in the men’s house for a period - the ritual and political heart of the village. Women are not allowed near. This is where men keep the ancestor figures, the masks, costumes and musical instruments. And where they teach the boys the traditions of the group. The boys undergo painful physical tests, such as tattooing and piercing of the nasal septum. Drums, flutes and bull-roarers provide music to accompany many of the secret rituals. Bull-roarers - wooden discs swung round above the head - zoom when swung and echo the voice of the ancestors.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Cosmos</STRONG><BR>\nSome rituals involve the whole community. An example is the ceremony of the Marind-anim - a Papuan people in the south of New Guinea. These ceremonies are performed to renew the Cosmos: dancers in magnificent costumes, each wearing or holding items that represent primeval beings, or demas, invigorate the life force of the Cosmos. These demas play a key role in the religious life of the Marind. Each clan has a primeval being as its original ancestor. It may be a kangaroo or a crane or an insect. A dema may be a plant, fire, or a celestial body. In short, everything that exists now originally stems from a dema. Marind clans hold creation rituals every one or more years, with participants depicting their own dema. Clan members can only portray their dema at creation rituals. Since the creation story features many different demas, the various clans - each with their own dema - have to coordinate the ritual together. These ceremonies are therefore an important channel for maintaining relations between various groups."^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
