<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/2a0744b54ff8467b9acd68892606d230> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "<STRONG>Religion: Life and Death</STRONG><BR>\nIn the course of the 20th century, European missionaries managed to convert most of the Papuan population to Christianity. After 1962, when control of New Guinea was transferred to Indonesia, Islam spread on the island. Until then, religious life among the inhabitants of New Guinea had revolved around ancestors and spirits. A wide variety of religious practices could be found among the different villages and peoples of the island, although these all had certain elements in common. Many Papuan objects in the museum collection relate to the old religions of New Guinea: ancestor figures, objects to ward off evil and objects used in rituals associated with gathering food, catching fish, initiating boys and with death.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Ancestors</STRONG><BR>\nSpirits and ancestors play a key role among the Papuan people. They are essential to the welfare of the group. They may punish the living with disease and calamity if neglected. So villagers venerate them by making offerings. A common practice among Papuans on New Guinea is to make wooden figures of ancestors, which contain the ancestor spirit. Villagers attempt to contact their ancestors through these figures, to ask for help in solving problems, curing disease and avoiding disaster. Ancestor symbols are found on arrowheads, musical instruments, head rests, benches and other objects. There is no sharp division between humans and animals in the world of ancestors. They may appear as a crocodile, a snake, a bird, or some other animal. These animal figures often have human characteristics, and people often have animal traits. <BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Spirits</STRONG><BR>\nReligious observance and votive objects are based on the assumption that invisible spirits and forces exist and can be manipulated. For Papuans, spirits are mainly active in the dark, in the forest, near rivers, in caves or on mountains. Papuans prefer to keep their distance from places where they believe spirits reside. They generally stay indoors at night.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Amulets</STRONG><BR>\nTo preserve good and ward off evil, Papuans have amulets. These are kept to protect against disease, to ensure a successful hunt or fishing expedition, to help trees and plants grow and provide food. Some carvings have the same effect, like the intricately sculpted bird figureheads that direct the fishermen’s craft, and the crocodile heads that make the war canoes as quick, stealth and dangerous as the crocodiles themselves."^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
