<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/2fb8562813c246e8a6db2513681ba755> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "<STRONG>Agriculture and Food</STRONG><BR>\nMost Papuans traditionally live in villages of little more than a hundred inhabitants. In the mountains, these are situated amid the fields in which villagers cultivate root crops such as sweet potato and taro. In addition to this staple, they grow vegetables, fruit, sugar cane and tobacco. Both men and women work in the fields; men are responsible for the fences that keep foraging pigs out, and for the irrigation ditches. Women have the daily task of finding firewood and preparing meals.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Sago</STRONG><BR>\nIn the marshland areas, sago is the principal food. Special beaters are used to remove the fibrous white marrow from the stem of the sago palm. The pulp-like mass is cleaned in long troughs made of tree bark. Mixed with fresh water, the sago is kneaded to make biscuits or porridge. This carbohydrate-rich diet is supplemented by an ample supply of coconuts, bananas and smaller domestic crops. <BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Hunting and fishing</STRONG><BR>\nPapuan women catch fish and crustaceans with net scoops in rivers and along the coast. Hunters catch wild pigs, marsupials, rodents and cassowaries for occasional meat meals. Hunters catch fish with multi-pronged spears, and shoot pigs with bamboo arrows cut to a sharp knife-edge. Arrows for shooting birds have blunt heads, to avoid damaging the plumage. <BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Preparation</STRONG><BR>\nMeat is generally a rare addition to the menu. It is cooked, packed in banana leaves and placed between hot stones in covered pit ovens. Sago biscuits are made on flat heated stones. Potatoes and root vegetables are baked in hot ash or in pit ovens, while fish are roasted over an open fire. Boiling in water is not a method used by Papuans, nor is frying in fat or oil. Salt is rare and is traded across vast distances. <BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Tools</STRONG><BR>\nAll the materials needed to make tools, clothes and ornaments are available in the surrounding environment: stone, wood, cane and bamboo, animal bones, animal teeth and claws, beaks and feathers, tortoiseshell, shells, grass stems, seeds and stones, bark and all kinds of fibres. Papuans use the same tools and weapons throughout New Guinea: digging sticks for preparing the soil in the highlands for new crops, heavy and light axes with sharpened stone blades for chopping trees and bushes, adzes for loosening soil and shaping planks to build houses and canoes, bows made of palm or bamboo and cane hunting arrows with palm or bamboo heads, and chisels, knives and scrapers made of stone, shell and bone."^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
