<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/45057b822753439abb0c5c844fba17c0> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "<STRONG>Spears from Southern Africa</STRONG><Br>\nSpears are among the most versatile and important objects in the material culture of many different peoples in Southern Africa and especially among Bantu language speaking peoples. Though Southern African spears may seem superficially similar, there is extraordinary variation in the design of spears depending on the people, the period, or the purpose for which the spear was made.<Br> \n<STRONG>Manufacture</STRONG><Br>\nThe simplest spears would have been made from wood with a fire-hardened tip. Southern African spears are more often made with iron blades. The general process of spear making consists of creating the haft of the spear from the wood of a suitable tree such as Curtisia dentata - commonly named the Assegai tree. A hole is bored into the haft using a red hot tool. Plant based glue is then inserted into the hole and then the tang, or body of the metal blade, is inserted. Finally, a binding made from plant fibre, animal hide, or metal is wound around the shaft to prevent it from splitting.<Br>\n<STRONG>As Tools</STRONG><Br>\nSpears were not exclusively or even primarily used for weapons as war. Spears were used for hunting either as thrown weapons or in close quarters. Spears were used in the place of knives and were useful in the slaughtering of animals for their meat and hides. Because of these diverse uses, there is a great variation in the types of spears - with the Zulu alone using some 20 variants, most intended for hunting. Khoisan peoples also used spears for hunting with the tips typically coated in plant derived poisons.<Br> \n<STRONG>Weapons of War</STRONG><Br>\nAs a weapon of war, spears from Southern Africa may be classified in two broad categories. The throwing spear is a light wooden spear with a fire-hardened wood or iron tip. These are often referred to as assegai, though the word was likely introduced by the Portuguese or Dutch. Alongside clubs, the throwing spear was probably the primary weapon among many Bantu-speaking peoples before the 19th century.<Br> \nThe change in spear design in the early 19th century is commonly attributed to the military reforms of the Zulu king Shaka kaSenzangakhona (ca. 1787 – 1828); though changes in military organization and tactics had already begun before Shaka’s reforms. Zulu tactics replaced the use of the throwing spear (called isijula in Zulu) with close quarters combat using the stabbing spear called iklwa. The name is supposedly derived from the sucking sound made when the weapon was pulled out of its victim. This type of spear is typically shorter and features a long and broad metal blade for its tip. Under Shaka’s successor Dingane kaSenzangakhona (ca. 1795–1840), the throwing spear returned and would be thrown at the enemy to break up enemy formations before charging in for close-quarters fighting using the stabbing spear. During Dingane’s reign the iklwa featured longer shafts and thinner blades.<Br> \nThis new type of warfare was incredibly successful. Warriors wielding the iklwa were depicted on Khoisan rock art from the period. The use of spears broadly corresponding to these two categories spread rapidly during the 19th century and within a few years these types of spears and tactics had spread as far as the Great Lakes region of Central and Eastern Africa.<Br> \nNorthern Ndebele spears tended to be broadly similar to Zulu spears but the Ndebele appear to have commissioned their spears from subject peoples. As a result, Ndebele spears feature influences from northern Zambesi metal work such as thick iron bindings where the tang enters the haft of the spear. These spears often feature a chisel shaped multi-purpose tool extending from the butt of the spear. Shona spears also feature metal bindings around the tang and sometimes these extend over the entire shaft of the spear; Tsonga spears are similar, being influenced by Shona designs.<Br>\nBy contrast the Basotho never adopted Zulu style weapons or tactics. The Basotho abandoned the use of shields in favour of guns and fighting on horseback and preferred much longer spears than the Zulu iklwa.<Br> \n<STRONG>Popular Culture</STRONG><Br>\nThe defeat of the British by Zulu impi at the Battle of Isandlwana (1879) further demonstrated the effectiveness of Zulu weapons and tactics. As a result of this battle the stereotypical image of the Zulu warrior, including his spear, became a widely disseminated image throughout Europe and the world from the 19th century to the present. This image has been frequently reproduced in popular depictions of South Africa. Informed by these depictions South African warfare, using spears, is often incorrectly interpreted as a form of primitive warfare and South African spears were often described as such in museum collections. However, as Isandlwana and other battles demonstrate this was not primitive warfare but modern warfare and a form of warfare flexible and powerful enough to inflict defeats on the world’s most powerful army. As a modern weapon the spear remained in widespread used as weapons until the late 20th century.<Br>\n<STRONG>Culture</STRONG><Br>\nIn Southern Africa spears have important symbolic value. Specially made spears are used to circumcise youths in some of the cultures, such as the Xhosa, where circumcision of boys is an important rite of passage. Because of their association with the military successes of the Zulu kingdom, spears are also potent political symbols. They are regarded, especially by some Zulu nationalists, as contemporary traditional and ceremonial weapons.<Br> \n<STRONG>Decline</STRONG><Br>\nDuring apartheid in South Africa, the spear was commonly associated with Zulu nationalism under the Inkatha party whose supporters often carried spears in public both as an expression of Zulu heritage but also as modern weapons. During the 1980s and early 1990s spears were often used in acts of political violence including in the infamous Boipatong massacre in 1992. As a result, the carrying of spears were severely curtailed by the 1990s.<Br>\n<STRONG>Symbols</STRONG><Br>\nBecause of their historical associations spears commonly feature in contemporary South African political symbols. In South Africa, the African National Congress (ANC) and Economic Freedom Fighters (EFF) parties depict spear on their logos. During the struggle against apartheid the ANC named its armed wing Umkhonto we Sizwe or Spear of the Nation. Spears are also featured in the coat of arms of Eswatini and the coat of arms of South Africa's KwaZulu-Natal province. Since 2000, a spear along with a knobkierie club are depicted in the South African coat of arms - though lying down, symbolizing peace.<Br>\nFDJvR, 28/03/2019<Br>\n\nLiterature:<Br> \nSpring, C. African Arms and Armour. British Museum Press, London, 1993. pp. 126-138."^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
