<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/4c3f3ca4306545568f70bd77ba990233> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Description in Dutch" .
<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/4c5641e55b60419ea16b9c49f9b8ddb5> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "In 1939, the museum became the home of an enormous and extremely significant collection of a collector who was guided purely and solely by his personal taste and artistic preferences. Georg Tillmann (1882–1941) was a German-Jewish banker who, distressed by political developments and growing anti-Semitism in his country, left his home in Hamburg as early as 1932 and moved to Amsterdam, where he settled in the old city centre. Soon afterwards, he became a Dutch citizen. <BR>\n<BR>\nIn Germany, the banker had been a fervent collector of expensive antiques, especially European porcelain. But once in the Netherlands, he came under the spell of what for him was unknown Indonesian art when his wife came home one day with a couple of beautiful Javanese krisses that she had bought for him in a shop a couple of blocks away. Not long after, Tillmann must have met Carel Groenevelt, a man who would spend a large part of his working life collecting, on commission, art objects from the Netherlands East Indies and New Guinea. <BR>\n<BR>\nTilmann’s visits to the Colonial Museum, where the cultures of the Netherlands East Indies had been placed on exhibit in all their variety and splendour by the museum’s inspired director, Van Eerde, must have fuelled his fascination for the artistic expressions of the East Indies to such an extent as to change the course of his collecting passion. <BR>\n<BR>\nIn 1933 Groenevelt, an uninhibited and adventurous man whose movements were not restricted by permanent employment, was asked by the very wealthy Tillmann to go ‘into the field’ to collect objects for him. Groenevelt subsequently departed for the Netherlands East Indies with what was for that time a very ample all-in budget: initially he received 10,000 guilders a month, which would later be reduced to 3,000 guilders when he had completed his journey and had settled with his wife on Java.<BR>\n<BR>\nHe would stay in the Netherlands East Indies for many years. Like clockwork, he would send the objects he had acquired to the Netherlands, especially old expensive fabric for which his client seemed to have a penchant. For his part, Tillmann did not travel, but added to his collection with purchases from specialized Dutch art dealers and at auctions, where he did not limit himself to objects from Indonesia. <BR>\n<BR>\nHe also made contacts with cultural ethnographic museums with which he could exchange a number of duplicate objects from his rapidly growing, high-quality collection. In the end, Tillmann’s collection became so large that he could not store it all in his own house and large garden house. He needed more space. So he leased a vacant building whose back garden adjoined his own back garden. By installing a door in his garden house, he easily gained access to this second house, where the majority of this collection was displayed as it would be in a museum. He managed his possessions as a professional collection curator would.<BR>\n<BR>\nIn putting together his collection, it seems that Tillmann was not only focused on the rarity or aesthetic quality of his pieces, but was just as much interested in their cultural historical value. Through his objects, he wanted to gain a better understanding of the culture from which they came:<BR>\n<BR>\n\"The tropical islands of the Dutch Empire – the ‘Girdle of Emeralds’ – inhabited by a population of 60 million people, varying from the most highly developed Hindu descendants to the most primitive Melanesians, have for 1,500 years produced a wealth of artistic utterances of which the world knows very little. All objects of these arts and crafts, in whatever material and from whatever period, for me have the same meaning as being inseparably connected with the rites, traditions and inner lives of their makers, sometimes obviously, mostly so mysteriously that access to their understanding is possible only with the help of intense ethnological and even psychoanalytical research work.\"<BR>\n<BR>\nTillmann studied a number of pieces in his collection and revealed himself to be a reasonably good researcher. He often obtained the advice of staff members at the Colonial Museum. Between 1936 and 1940, he wrote nine short articles in the magazines Maandblad voor Beeldende Kunsten (‘Monthly for the Plastic Arts’) and Cultureel Indië (‘The Cultural Indies’), published under the auspices of the Colonial Institute. Seven of these articles were on Indonesian fabrics and the significance of the symbolic ornamentation.<BR>\n<BR>\nTo stay one step ahead of the approaching war, Tillmann left for England with his family in 1939 with the intention of returning to the Netherlands in the future. He was able to place his valuable objects in the custody of the Colonial  Museum, where they were hidden among the museum’s own possessions in the depots. This is why the collection survived the war without being noticed by the German occupiers. <BR>\n<BR>\nTillmann, who had left everything behind in Amsterdam with a heavy heart, would never again see his exotic treasures. He died after an operation in New York, where the family had settled not long before. As a gesture of thanks for the care and management of the collection during the war years, the family gave the collection to the museum in 1946. It was still in Amsterdam, in a long- term loan arrangement for the purposes of study and exhibition. At that time, the museum launched the extensive documentation of the objects under the new serial number 1772, which have since been exhibited and published many times both in the Netherlands and abroad. <BR>\n<BR>\nIn 1994, Tillmann’s widow and son decided to donate the entire collection to the Tropenmuseum, with the request that a special exhibition be devoted to it with an accompanying book. The temporary exhibition and eponymous book appeared in 1996: A Passion for Indonesian Art; The George Tillmann Collection (1882–1941) at the Tropenmuseum in Amsterdam. The exhibition was limited to a selection from the hundreds of Indonesian fabrics. The book covers the entire collection. With the donation of this collection, which consists of more than 2,000 objects, the Tropenmuseum obtained one of its most significant acquisitions ever. Many of the objects from the Tillmann collection are also on permanent display. Understandably, the collection of Georg Tillmann is often identified with the majority of its objects which come from Indonesia. But the collection also contains objects from the Americas, Africa, South and South-East Asia and Oceania. <BR>\n<BR>\nGeorg Tillmann bought what he considered to be beautiful; so there is no special focus in his collection. Nonetheless, all objects have special aspects or remarkable details, making this collection one of exceptional quality and significance.<BR>\n<BR>\nSource: Duuren, David van, 'The Top Collections of Georg Tillmann and Gijsbert Oudshoorn', in: David van Duuren et al., Oceania at the Tropenmuseum, Amsterdam 2011, pp. 138-146.<BR>\nRead more: Brakel, Koos van, David van Duuren, Itie van Hout \"A Passion for Indonesian Art: The Georg Tillmann (1882-1941) Collection at the Tropenmuseum Amsterdam\". Amsterdam, KIT Publishers, 1996"^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
