<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/5d51b85366e24a1a9137d84a66637a42> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "<STRONG>Maroons are the descendants in Suriname of Africans who escaped the slavery of the plantations. Their African origins are clearly recognisable in their religion. Over the years they also adopted elements from the religion of the original Native Americans of the region as well as newcomers who settled in Suriname. The precise details of the religion may differ from person to person. Yet there are some general features of Maroon religion which can be clearly identified.</STRONG><br>\n<br>\n<STRONG>Gods</STRONG><br>\nMaroon religion has one supreme god: Gaan Gadu or Nana. Various lesser gods govern the elements of air, water and earth. The demigods are grouped under three main sections - one for each element - with a series of subsidiary deities. At the same time, there are gods who are associated with particular locations, such as the forest or water. <br>\n<br>\n<STRONG>Ancestors</STRONG><br>\nMaroons have a special connection with their ancestors: the yooka. Altars dedicated to the yooka are the focus of various rituals. These altars are generally located in front of the building in which corpses are laid before burial. <br>\n<br>\n<STRONG>Obia</STRONG><br>\nContact with the gods is through an obiaman. He combines the role of priest, medium, doctor, psychologist and herbalist. The way an obiaman contacts the spirit world is through trance. He is able to speak on behalf of the gods and relate their messages. Another form of contact is through oracles, which involves the priest consulting an array of magical objects. An implement that is often used in rituals is the buii, an armband with spiritual powers. Occasionally, obia (magic) is used for negative purposes, to inflict evil on someone, for example.  <br>\n<br>\n<STRONG>About Maroons</STRONG><br>\nThe Maroons who live in the Surinamese interior today are descendants of Africans who were enslaved to work on plantations. Their ancestors had managed to escape from the plantations into Suriname's impenetrable forest in the 17th and 18th century. They fled upstream along the rivers, where the planters were unable to track them. Eventually, six distinct groups of Maroons emerged: the Auka or Ndyuka, Saramakka, Paramakka, Kwiinti, Matawai and the Aluku, also known as Boni. In the 1760s, these groups concluded a peace treaty with the Dutch colonial regime."^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
