<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/8e14866cc8ca41b7a3e9dcc5fee25b73> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "Candomblé<br>\nCandomblé is a Brazilian religion: a mixture of African, Christian (Catholic) and indigenous Brazilian religious ideas and rituals. Like Vodou on Haiti, Winti in Suriname and Santería on Cuba, the religion emerged in the period in which Africans were enslaved and brought to the New World. It was then that African religions mixed with the other religions there. The African roots of Candomblé can be traced to the Yoruba culture of West Africa. <br>\n<br>\nOrixas<br>\nThe Portuguese word candomblé comes from the Bantu word kandombele (Bantu is a family of African languages). Kandombele means a place for prayer, or a music and dance festival.<br>\nThe principal Candomblé gods are the orixas. These were brought over from Africa to Brazil by the transported Africans. Worshippers gather in Candomblé temples, terreiros, to perform rituals for the orixas or to ask for their help. During temple services, mediums and congregants become possessed by orixas, and go into a trance. They then personify the gods that possess them, allowing others to see and speak to the orixas at these ceremonies.  <br>\n<br>\nNations<br>\nBrazilian plantation-owners allowed people with related African origins to remain together. These groups formed nations with their own rulers and administrations. That was different in North America and under Dutch and Spanish rule, where Africans of similar descent were deliberately separated to stifle resistance and rebellion. <br>\nThe various forms of Candomblé are based around these different nations.<br>\n <br>\nSalvador da Bahia<br>\nThe hub of the Portuguese slave trade was at Salvador da Bahia. The first Africans were brought to Salvador by the Portuguese in 1538 to work in the mines, on the plantations and as servants in the homes of Europeans. The influence of these Africans and their descendants is therefore greatest in this city and province of Bahia.<br>\n<br>\nAbolition of slavery<br>\nThis form of human trafficking was outlawed in Brazil in 1850. Slavery itself was not abolished until 1888. A huge migration to the main cities followed. However, there was little work to be found, since Brazil had no industrial infrastructure. Moreover, most employers preferred to take on skilled workers from Europe and Japan. As a result, the freed Africans had a hard time building a new life."^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
