<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/977186481a0b49418d9bd68c086a4197> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "While not as common as the use of spears and clubs, battle axes were used in Southern African warfare. Southern African axes were typically used in close quarters combat; throwing axes existed but were less common. As weapons, the design of Southern African axes is derived from domestic tools such as hoes and adzes. Southern African battle axes typically feature a long wooden handle with a knob on the end - very similar to South African clubs, called knobkerries, which could be used as either clubs or handles for axes. The head of Southern African axes is usually made from iron, though other materials such as aluminum or sheet metal are used in more modern ceremonial axes.<Br>\n \nThe overall design of Southern African axes is highly variable between different peoples and depending on its use. In addition to being used as weapon of war, axes could be used for hunting; were carried as objects of rank and status; and among some peoples had symbolic and ritual uses. These latter types of axes often featured elaborate decorations.<Br>\n\nLiterature:<Br> \nSpring, C. African Arms and Armour. British Museum Press, London, 1993. pp. 126-138."^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
