<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/9893bd00e8a94b35be2824b46ac745a5> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Description in English" .
<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/98f61211deaf4bb0857f4ee2014531eb> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "The hidden base of Borobudur\nBorobudur, a Buddhist monument founded around 800 AD on the island of Java, has a pride of place on the UNESCO World Heritage list. Borobudur is a visual image of the Buddhist cosmology - an overview of the living worlds within the cycle of transmigration, kept forever in motion by the universal law of Cause and result. The external form is that of a stupa, the most characteristic type of Buddhist monument built as dedication to the Buddha. The stupa of Borobudur consists of many square and round terraces, supporting a single dome-like structure at the top. The terraces and their sculptural contents are symbolic of the three levels in a Buddhist system of cosmology, being the World of Desires (Kamadhatu), the World of Form without Desires (Rupadhatu), and the ultimate World of Formlessness (Arupadhatu), constituting simultaneously the three steps of spiritual progress towards Salvation. The sculptured reliefs form an integral part of the symbolic meaning of Borobudur, dealing with the very ground rule of Buddhist ethics: the immutable Law of Action and Result (karma). This is operative in the World of Desires in terms of reward and retribution. \n\nMany records made by Europeans are known from early 19th century. In 1885, archaeologists discovered another base behind the outer wall of the lowest terrace of Borobudur, which was found to be faced with 160 panels of narrative stone reliefs. The 'hidden base' was uncovered and photographed in 1890-91, then was again covered. Only three of the reliefs can be seen today. More than any other sets of sculptures at Borobudur, these reliefs reproduce the cultural and social environments of Java of c. 800 AD. Side by side with the conventional scenes of Heaven and Hell, there are depictions of earthly ideologies and wishful desires, of worldly successes and miseries, of things good and bad in everyday life that are themselves consequential of what has been done in the past, and will bring their own fruition either as reward or retribution. A mystery, nevertheless, remains to be explained as to why these reliefs became encased in a new walkway of stone, before they were ompleted. \n\n\nReward and retribution \nAccording to the Buddhist world view, as expressed in these reliefs, both reward and retribution become operative from the new birth. Buddhist cosmology enumerates six worlds of existence within the Realm of Desires (Kamadhatu), where all actions are irrefutably followed by consequences. \nAbove the world of human beings, are the higher and happier worlds of the gods and the semi-gods. The gods are believed to enjoy an immeasurable long life in perfect health and beauty, immune of bodily change, heat or cold, hunger or thirst. The worlds of the semi-gods \nare described as almost as pleasant as those of the gods, but the inhabitants are still afflicted by certain negative feelings of dissatisfaction, depression and restlessness. In the human world, wisdom and follies, good and evil, and joy and sorrow intermingle. The living condition in human life varies according to the nature of the previous deeds. Man has the capacity of reasoning and choice of action that will affect their future. The lower and unhappy world of the animals partly overlaps that of man, who has variant kinds of relationship with them. Below the world of the animals, lies the world of the miserable hungry ghosts who are \nconstantly tormented by hunger and thirst, heat and cold. In the deepest depth of the Universe is situated the hell, where gruesome punishments are meted out as retributions for the worst kinds of evil-doers. The types, degree and length of sufferings in hell depend on the types and the severity of the crime the person has committed. \n\nHappiness and success in the world of man \nLife as a human being is already a great reward in itself, but there are varieties of living circumstances. A long life, blessed with a happy and complete family of wives and children, supported by wealth that finances luxurious mansion full of servants, plenty of food and drink, respect from others, relaxation and entertainment, are considered ideal living situations for all social classes of human beings. \nA birth in heaven, where the inhabitants are imagined to have an immensely long life, possess an immaculately beautiful and glorious body, unimpaired by physical defects or changes, to enjoy all conceivable kinds of sensual pleasures, is the highest and most pleasant living situation imagined by man. \n\nWealth and luxury \nA rich and presumably happy man can be recognized by his elaborate garment and ornaments, and is frequently shown in fond company of his wives and children, seated at ease on a seat or throne in front of which lie chests of treasures, large bowls and other containers of edibles and wealth. He is usually attended by a bevy of servants, male and female, fanning him or bringing more luxury goods or precious gifts. His living apartment is shown as beautifully decorated, and presumably well-scented with fragrance of fresh flowers, garlands and perfumed ointments, emulating the pleasantness of a terrace that opens into the flowering pleasure garden round his mansion. Royal environment is a more sumptuous version of the \nliving sphere of the rich, further enhanced by paraphernalia of royalty. A feast in an affluent household would have been replete or even excessive with much food and drink, music and dance and other forms of sensual delights. Persons with pious inclinations invited religious persons to their home for meal and alms, or sponsored merit-making feasts and brought \nspecial gifts to their residences. When going out the rich and the mighty are usually attended by servants and/or bodyguards carrying sun-shade or other symbols of rank. The very wealthy and royal personages travel in style on a carried litter, on horseback or on an elephant, accompanied by a large retinue. \n\nPoverty, toils and hardship \nBesides bad health, untimely death, loss of possession and torments in hell, bad actions lead to an unhappy new birth among the poor who have to labour hard for their livelihood. We see them toiling as farmers, hunters of small games, collectors of fruits and other products of the soil, street performers, vendors, peddlers, beggars and other receivers of alms. The lack of money, nevertheless, can be compensated by a warm family life, while sympathy and generosity among the poor themselves will also lead to a happy future. \nUgly appearance, deformity, stupidity, indolent disposition, lethargy and inertia are considered as consequences of bad actions. Such unhappy human beings suffer not only through physical defects, poverty and failure in life, but even more from contempt, repulsion, derision, and unreasonable aggression launched on them by prejudiced society that regards deformity and ugliness as repulsive and even fearsome. \n\nPastime and amusement \nMusic, dance and theatre probably formed a major part of pastime and recreations. Professional groups are shown many times to be part of everyday life. Acrobatic feats, too, seem to have been popular among the mass. More refined forms of performances obviously entertained wealthy and royal households, and were imagined to be part of heavenly \npleasures as well. \nGambling, mentioned in 14th century Javanese literature to take place on a large scale at the close of a grand state ceremony, could have been a type of pastime for certain groups of people during the 9th century. Religious festivals presumably constituted an enjoyable facet of social life, participated by the entire community. Pleasure gardens for public recreations must have existed, made pleasant with plants, shrubs, flowering trees, and lotus ponds accommodating birds and aquatic lives, for people with leisure to come to stroll and enjoy themselves. Inscriptions of Java frequently mention flowers and trees in temple-complexes \nand around residences of religious persons. These were considered to have salubrious and beneficial influences on the body and the mind. \n\nNature and architecture \nThis series of reliefs present several scenes that were most probably taken from real life, envisaged against the background of Javanese environment of ca. 9th century. Flora and fauna, inseparable from human life, have been incorporated in almost all scenarios. Trees occur in profusion and varieties. Many trees and plants can be identified with true botanical species. \nFlowers, especially lotuses, served as choice offerings to temples and as tributes to rich householders. Fresh flowers and garlands arranged in vases or on trays, welcomed honoured guests, and enhanced illustrious gatherings. Animals and birds are seen in their natural surroundings, as well as being domesticated for company, food and transport. Elephants \nobviously served as royal mounts on ceremonial occasions. The most common types of domestic building shown in these reliefs are the typical wooden pillared pendopo which we still see everywhere in Indonesia, or small thatched houses standing on poles. More sumptuous buildings in permanent materials of stone and brick, standing for temples and monasteries, were probably modelled on the existing religious architecture of the time. \n\nProfessed norm of Buddhist practice and piety \nThe priest-designer of Borobudur and the sculptors of the reliefs made use of Indian texts, especially the Karmavibhanga, as guidelines for their visual presentation. The basic codes of Buddhist ethics pervade through these panels. We are constantly reminded of the five commandments of not killing but saving lives, not stealing, no lewd or unlawful sexual conducts, no deceitful, malicious nor slanderous words, and no intoxicants. Other rules of moral behaviours, prescribing respect to parents, teachers, elderly persons and religious men of all creeds, are also underlined time and again. The emphasis, nevertheless, lies heavily on charity and generosity, especially to Buddhist monks and Buddhist monasteries, who are the \nmaintainers and promulgators of the doctrine of the Buddha. \nIn spite of the repetitive enumeration of material rewards, primarily defined as great wealth and heavenly pleasure, the Karmavibhanga text repeatedly states that all these are not the ultimate goal of life, but form a step towards the ultimate goal: nirwana. We notice that in many scenes of great wealth and material enjoyment, the main character wears a special type of band, known as yogapatta (meditation band) in Indian tradition, around the hip, and often turns his face away from the enticing spectacles, or assumes a contemplative or even meditative attitude. In many instances, a temple is conspicuously present as a focus or an important component of the scene. All these give visual allusions to the state of Salvation (nirwana) that should always be the ultimate goal of human life. The closing panel of the series brings out this message even more clearly by placing figures of four meditating \nrecluses in the same panel as that of paradise, obviously to underline the abandonment of all pleasures for spiritual progress upwards, to the higher planes of existence and to the ultimate nirwana." .
