<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/9e9daf8b279b41a68f7e4f434446918d> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "<I><STRONG>Five facts concerning the Dutch royal family and the colonies.</I></STRONG>\n<I>Many photographs from the Tropenmuseum collection show, royal family related festivities in the former colonies . Many flags and signs show W’s for Willem or Wilhelmina. Notoriously missing in the photographs are the monarchs themselves. In the Netherlands East Indies, not a single Dutch monarch ever set foot. Not until 1955 did queen Juliana visit Suriname and the Antilles.</I><BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Absent</STRONG><BR>\nThough physically the House of Orange did not attend any of these festivities in the East and West Indies, symbolically they were all over. Portraits and busts of the ruling monarchs could be found in court houses, municipality halls and other important facilities.\nThe images of the Tropenmuseum suggest a common Orange sentiment in the colonies, but they are misleading. The Indo-European community loved the royal family out of free will. Only a few other minority groups, such as the Christian Moluccans, would sing Wilhelmus, the national anthem, voluntarily.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Symbolic</STRONG><BR>\nIn Suriname and the Antilles, the family of Orange had an extra symbolic value. King William III signed the Emancipation Law in 1863, that proclaimed all those enslaved to be free. That strongly associated the Dutch Royal family with emancipation from slavery, though the 19th century Orange family was hardly openly against slavery.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>In the Netherlands</STRONG><BR>\nNaturally the Dutch monarchs were involved in the colonies. In 1926, Wilhelmina opened the Colonial Institute and the Colonial Museum in Amsterdam (now the Royal Tropical Institute and the Tropenmuseum). And the official transfer of sovereignty to Indonesia was signed by queen Juliana, in the Royal Palace at Dam Square, Amsterdam.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Royal vessel</STRONG><BR>\nInterest from the colonies for royal affairs can be illustrated by a photograph, dated around queen Wilhelmina’s inauguration. This photograph was taken from an album from the Netherlands East Indies, and depicts young Wilhelmina entering the conspicuous royal vessel on 15 September 1898.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Too hot</STRONG><BR>\nFor a brief moment it appeared that Wilhelmina was to undertake a trip to the Netherlands East Indies. In June 1940, after Wilhelmina and her ministers were transferred to London, there was a plan to move the government to Batavia, capital of the Netherlands East Indies. However, Wilhelmina was quick to inform her minister of Foreign Affairs, Van Kleffens, that “I am not going, as I cannot stand the heat”."^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
