<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/a5c03fdd48a24b73b5a61c0a8c8ba909> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "<STRONG>Gijsbertus Oudshoorn (1894–1965) was an enthusiastic collector who switched his passion from European Art to tribal art. Oudshoorn didn’t change course until after the Second World War, when he had already passed the age of fifty. He led an unremarkable life that is flimsily documented. What we do know about him is what he – and later his widow – chose to tell to Dutch journalists who, shortly before his death, devoted several newspaper and magazine articles to him and his magnificent collection. Oudshoorn is characterized in these articles as a simple man.</STRONG><BR>\n<BR>\nThe Dutch art critic Hans Redeker visited him in December 1964 for his weekly newspaper column ‘Bij Nederlandse verzamelaars’ (‘With Dutch collectors’) in The Hague where he lived. Redeker was received in a home...<BR>\n<BR>\n<i>\"that is difficult to imagine being less remarkable.\nA small, dreary square in an ugly, drab neighbourhood filled with ordinary houses... with... a landing and a door among the hundred thousand other landings and doors. A simple nameplate appears: OUDSHOORN.\"</i><BR>\n<BR>\nIt was the home of a man who had worked his entire unadventurous life at the same bank and had risen there from being the youngest employee to the position of cashier. After taking early retirement, he continued working as an art critic for two Dutch newspapers for a number of years. Redeker’s description of the home in The Hague seems to suggest that Oudshoorn had denied himself many other pleasures in life for the sake of his passion, as he had become fascinated by art at a young age. It was an interest that was accompanied by an urge to buy that was alien to the simple environment from which he came. In the words of Redeker:<BR>\n<BR>\n<i>\"We see a young office clerk who walked through the streets of The Hague and timidly looked through the windows of art shops. He later plucked up the courage to go inside to make his first purchase. His wife still remembers when, three months before their wedding, he cheerfully came to tell her that he had spent all of their savings, which had been put aside for furniture, on a series of etchings in a shop...that was going out of business.\"</i><BR>\n<BR>\nOudshoorn soon became a familiar figure in The Hague’s art circles and he made friends among avant-garde Dutch artists such as Willem van Konijnenburg, from whom he purchased his first painting in 1927. The works of Jan Toorop and a number of young Dutch modernists such as Piet Ouborg, Willem Hussem and Co Westerik would follow. Later Oudshoorn would look beyond the confines of the Dutch art world and buy work from artists such as Odilon Redon, Marc Chagall, Raoul Dufy and Alexander Archipenko with the money he had scraped together. It was during the depression of the 1930s; the works of these masters of modern art, whose value would be astronomical later, could be bought for a few tens of guilders. Inspired by the works of these painters, Oudshoorn’s interests gradually turned to tribal art from Africa and Oceania.<BR>\n<BR>\nFor twenty years after the Second World War, he passionately collected this art by selling or exchanging a number of his paintings, whose value had skyrocketed by then. In a number of cases, an artwork sold for a hundred times what Oudshoorn had paid for it only 15 to 20 years earlier. Up until the day he died, buying and selling, exchanging and saving, he built up one of the most impressive private collections of non-Western art that could be found in the Netherlands.<BR>\n<BR>\nGijs Oudshoorn died in 1965, soon after Redeker and other journalists had brought him a little fame outside his own network of art collectors. His wife kept the collection together for the most part – her only capital – for another eight years. Then, forced by a lack of money, in the early 1970s she approached the Geographic and Ethnographic Museum in Rotterdam, and then the Tropenmuseum. For financial reasons, the negotiations with the Rotterdam museum reached an impasse, despite a curator there having written a strong argument in an internal report to his director urging him to acquire the collection. Limiting himself to the African objects, he stressed their high quality, sometimes their singularity, their large style purity and good condition. He also pointed out that the provenance of some of the pieces went back to the possession of famous artists from the beginning of the 20th century, including Andre Derain and Jacob Epstein, which meant that the objects not only had an African cultural history value, but also a European cultural value:<BR>\n<BR>\n<i>\"A high museum value can be attributed to the Oudshoorn collection in its entirety (seen from a range of perspectives), which would make its acquisition by any museum a reason for great joy. For the Geographic and Ethnographic Museum there is the added benefit that this collection does not duplicate the museum’s current collection in any way.\"</i><BR>\n<BR>\nMoreover, the last comment particularly pertains to the Tropenmuseum because, due to its history as a colonial museum, in 1973 it still had a very limited Africa collection with few real highlights. A number of top artistic pieces from this part of the world were therefore more than welcome. And they were top pieces that could no longer be collected in Africa because the cultural areas from which they came had been completely cleaned out in this regard. But the offer of the Oudshoorn collection came to the Tropenmuseum during its transitional years, a period in which the museum transformed itself, with some pressure from the ministerial subsidy provider, into a museum in which the prevailing events and needs of the Third World could be represented. So was there still any interest in purchasing traditional art? Definitely, according to the director, J.H. Jager Gerlings, who considered the high quality of the traditional collection of great importance...<BR>\n<BR>\n\"<i>...because, in the changing societies in the tropics and subtropics, the element of identity loss, the search for a new identity, the success and failure of this search, is often an undercurrent that, when recognized, explains many development problems and makes them understandable. It is essential that the public is shown in the museum that the societies in the tropics and subtropics once possessed or still possess a different, but not less valuable culture, that these cultures evolve just as our own culture does. The Tropenmuseum wants to show people how these cultures evolve. The museum can do justice to these cultures and societies only when the quality of the objects which illustrate these developments and changes is as high as possible.\"</i><BR>\n<BR>\nThe Tropenmuseum entered negotiations with the widow Oudshoorn and the parties came to an agreement. In order to purchase the collection, the museum would have to dig deep into its purse and that would mean a couple of lean years ahead for the museum because the amount agreed swallowed up several annual budgets. Fortunately, the amount of the purchase could be paid in instalments, the last of which was remitted by Mrs Oudshoorn in 1975. She died in 1984 and legally bequeathed to the Tropenmuseum another small collection of Eastern art objects.<BR>\n<BR>\nThe 419 items in the Oudshoorn collection emphasize the African element: 107 sublime objects. Yet no less sublime is the smaller Pacific part of the collection with 37 objects – masks, ancestral figures, amulets, jewellery, old ceremonial clubs – taken from the Sepik region in Papua New Guinea, the south and north coast of Papua and the islands in the Pacific located further to the east. Here too we see a similarity with the Tillmann collection due to the absence of any focus or theme: Oudshoorn added to his collection what he considered to be beautiful. So in addition to African and Pacific art, he also collected Javanese wayang masks, Japanese prints and theatre masks, and antique bronze objects from Iran. Yet, according to Hans Redeker, the collection did have a Leitmotiv that said something about the collector himself...<BR>\n<BR>\n\"<i>and the manner in which he appears in seventy to eighty masks: his interest in the human face, the other face that reveals itself in dance masks, in the heads of ancestors and the almost demonic theatre masks of the Japanese Noh theatre.\"</i><BR>\n<BR>\nThe new acquisition of the Tropenmuseum was shown to the public from October to December 1973 in the exhibition ‘Anonymous artists from a far away world’ (‘Anonieme kunstenaars uit een verre wereld’); a small selection from it was discussed in the eponymous exhibition catalogue. Since then, a number of objects from the former collection of Gijsbert Oudshoorn, registered under serial number TM-4133, have been exhibited in the museum permanently. A handful of object from Oudshoorn's collection can be found in the collections of the Wereldmuseum Rotterdam, while others, same as the Tropenmuseum Collection did, entered the Collection Nationaal Museum van Wereldculturen via the Leiden Museum of Ethnology and the former Museum Nusantara.<BR>\n<BR>\nSource: Duuren, David van, 'The Top Collections of Georg Tillmann and Gijsbert Oudshoorn', in: David van Duuren et al., Oceania at the Tropenmuseum, Amsterdam 2011, pp. 138-146.<BR>\nRead more: 'Gijsbertus Oudshoorn (1894–1965)', in: Faber, Paul, Africa at the Tropenmuseum, Amsterdam 2013, p. 39"^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
