<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/a914cf320c6f44f69236e7f5987fc7e9> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Identification number" .
<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/aaba5c61bac3455095158bb0de7dcf1b> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "Southern African clubs are commonly referred to as ‘knobkerries’ in English. The term is derived from Afrikaans ‘knopkierie’ which in turn derives from the Afrikaans word ‘knop’ (knob) and the Khoekhoe or San word kirri meaning walking stick. These clubs typically have a long shaft and a rounded or oval knob on one end. They are used both as clubs and throwing weapons. Historically, the use of knobkerries was most prominent among Nguni peoples although nearly all South African peoples have a history of knobkerrie use.<Br>\n\nAmong the Zulu these wooden clubs are known as iwisa and feature spherical knobs. In the 19th century, iwisa were only occasionally used as weapons of war, usually as a substitute for the more commonly used isijula or throwing spear. Though little used in war, they were an important part of Zulu material culture and were commonly carried as symbols of authority, or used as ceremonial objects. As decorative and ceremonial objects knobkerries are sometimes elaborately decorated. One variant of the knobkerrie is where the knob is replaced by a snuff box.<Br>\n\nZulu style weapons and tactics were widely adopted by neighbouring groups and as a result the use of knobkerries tend to be similar among many Southern African peoples. The Northern Ndebele people used the nduku which was similar to the Zulu iwisa in both design and use. Tsonga clubs were also similar but featured both Zulu style spherical heads, and in places such as southern Mozambique, oval shaped heads. Among the Northern Ndbele the knobkerrie, or nduku, was often fashioned into the handle of battle axes. \n\nOne exception to the Zulu style use of knobkerries is the Basotho under Moshoeshoe (ca. 1786 - 1870) who did commonly use the knobkerrie as a weapon and as such it was typically carried by Basotho warriors. Sotho knobkerries are generally much simpler in design and ornamentation than that of neighbouring peoples and they are often regarded as highly important symbols of one's personal identity and connection with their ancestors. The larger koto and the smaller kotjane typically feature a straight shaft with a circular and centrally positioned knob. In ornamental knobkerries the shaft is sometimes decorated with wirework and in some cases a mirror may be placed on the knob. These designs are more recent and knobkerries with these designs are typically used as decorative objects only. <Br>\n\nDuring the apartheid period, the Zulu nationalist movement Inkatha regarded the iwisa, along with Zulu spears, as traditional weapons and lobbied for the right to carry them in public. Unlike spears which saw a decline in use in the late 20th century, the knobkerrie remains widely used in the 21st century, especially in rural areas of Southern Africa, but it is also frequently carried by protestors.<Br>\n\nIn 20th century and contemporary Southern Africa the knobkerrie is commonly featured on national symbols. It featured on the flag of the nominally independent Republic of Ciskei, which is now part of South Africa. Knobkerries were also depicted on the flag of Lesotho from 1987 to 2006 and still feature on the Lesotho coat of arms and royal standard. In South Africa, a knobkerrie is featured alongside a spear on the Order of Mendi for Bravery, the coat of arms of the KwaZulu-Natal province, and also alongside a spear on the South African coat of arms, both lying down symbolizing peace.<Br>\nF.D. Janse van Rensburg, 06/05/2019<Br>\n\nSpring, C. African Arms and Armour. British Museum Press, London, 1993. pp. 126-138."^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
