<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/c2f0b1a9280d484cace9077d4fc168a2> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "<STRONG>Slavery has existed throughout history and in every culture. Around the world, the powerful have oppressed the weak against their will and with violence for their own benefit. Slavery still exists today in various forms: sadly, one form that occurs frequently is child labour.</STRONG><br>\nA well-known example is the slavery of the Africans who were shipped to North and South America and the Caribbean islands. They had been transported there in Spanish, English and Dutch vessels since the 16th century. Most of the Africans laboured on huge agricultural estates; others were forced to into mines, while some were made to work in the cities.<br>\n<br>\n<STRONG>Human Traffic</STRONG><br>\nLocal traders on the coast of West Africa bought captives from the African hinterland and sold them to European traffickers. Around eleven million Africans were transported in this way to North and South America, the Antilles and other Caribbean islands.<br>\nAround six percent of these were transported across the ocean on Dutch ships: about 600,000 people. Half of these went to Suriname, the Antilles and Guyana. The rest were sold.<br>\nThey were not large ships. The people were packed into cramped overcrowded holds. Many died on the voyage. Those who survived were sold in America and branded with the initials of their plantation or owner.  Their owners often gave them a new, European name. <br>\n<br>\n<STRONG>Resistance</STRONG><br>\nSlavery often led to resistance. Strikes and rebellions by enslaved people were the answer to the violence of their masters. Some managed to escape. They fled the plantations and reclaimed their freedom. From the island of Curaçao they crossed to the mainland, to Venezuela. In Suriname, those who managed to get away from the estates formed settlements in the forests of the hinterland. Many of their descendants, known as Maroons, still live there and recall their ancestors with pride.<br>\n<br>\n<STRONG>Abolition</STRONG><br>\nBritain banned the trade in African slaves in 1808. In the Netherlands, it was outlawed in 1814. Yet many thousands of Africans continued to be shipped to Suriname well into the 1830s - illegally. Meanwhile, on the plantations slavery continued. It was not until 1834 and 1848 that France and Britain abolished slavery as an institution. The Dutch waited until 1 July 1863. The act is celebrated each year by Surinamers in the keti koti festival. <br>\nSuriname's slave-owners received 300 guilders in compensation for each liberated person. The freed themselves received nothing: in fact, they still had to work another ten years for a meagre wage on their old plantations.<br>\n<BR>\nGet to know more about slavery:\n<a href=\"http://collectie.wereldculturen.nl/?query=search=Deeplink identifier=site_7&showtype=record\">- Life on the plantations</a><BR>\n<a href=\"http://collectie.wereldculturen.nl/?query=search=Deeplink identifier=site_9&showtype=record\">- Afro-American religions</a><BR>\n<a href=\"http://collectie.wereldculturen.nl/?query=search=Deeplink identifier=site_10&showtype=record\">- Marroons en religion</a><BR>\n<a href=\"http://collectie.wereldculturen.nl/?query=search=Deeplink identifier=site_11&showtype=record\">- Brasilian religion</a><BR>"^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
