<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/cd92477eb1184148a874c909a27065ae> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "Introduction\nThe Southern African shields in the collection of the Nationaal Museum van Wereldculturen and Wereldmuseum all appear to be variants of the Nguni-type shield. These shields are best known for being used by the Zulu people, but the design was also used by many other Southern African peoples. It is not the only well-known Southern African shield design but other designs, such as Sotho-type shields, are not present in the collection.\n\nManufacture\nNguni shields are oval shaped, and typically made from cowhide, which is preferably cut from the back of the animal where the hide is thickest. The hide is tanned to give it durability. In the 19th century this would have involved drying the hide in the sun until it was stiff, then burying it in manure, then pounding it with sticks until supple. Finally, the resulting leather is cut into an oval shape to make the front of the shield.\n\nNguni shields are carried with a stick which functions as a handle. The stick is attached to the shield with leather strips. These strips are often a different colour from the leather of the shield. This creates a row of contrasting marks in the centre of the shield which also functions as a decorative element. A second layer of leather is placed behind the stick to create a double layered shield with the stick in between.\n\nHistorically Nguni shields were multi-purpose tools. They were used in hunting and warfare but shields also had decorative, symbolic, and ritual value. As a result, several different varieties exist to suit the different uses of the shield. The varieties are primarily distinguished by their different sizes and colours.\n\nZulu Shields\nThe Zulu regarded the shield as the most important part of a warrior’s equipment. During the reign of Shaka kaSenzangakona (ca. 1816-1828), Zulu warriors carried the large (ca. 1.5 metre) isihlangu shield which could also be used offensively to hook an opponent’s shield away in hand to hand fighting. However, the most important use of the shield was as protection, not only for the warrior carrying the shield, but also to provide protection for the warrior on the left. \n\nBy the mid-19th century, the smaller but sturdier umbumbuluzo (ca. 1.1 metre) began to replace the isihlangu. This was likely due to the increased use of guns and horses in Southern African warfare which required greater mobility. A commonly repeated myth in South Africa is that Zulu shields could be made bullet proof by dipping the shield in water, but there is no evidence that this was an actual tactic used by the Zulu.\n\nBesides their use in combat, Zulu shields also had other military uses. The colour and pattern of the cowhide could be used to indicate regimental affiliation. The youngest warriors had black shields, while the most senior warriors carried pure white shields made from cattle of the Zulu king’s own herds. Before battle, warriors would bang their spears on shields to intimidate the enemy. Shields also had more practical uses: warriors would sleep under their shields at night and use them for shade in the day.\n\nSymbols\nIn addition to their military use, shields had symbolic and ritual value. Certain rituals in the Zulu religion involved shields. Smaller shields were used in dancing ceremonies, or carried by young men during courtship. \n\nNguni shields are no longer used in warfare, having become largely obsolete by the late 19th century. The symbolic use of shields continues in the 21st century. Shields continue to be used in traditional rituals and ceremonies. For example a small shield is carried by the bride during traditional Zulu wedding ceremonies, and small shields are also carried during certain ceremonies of the Amanazaretha Church. \n\nAs political symbols, Nguni shields commonly feature on flags and coat of arms in Southern Africa. For example a shield is featured prominently on the flag of Eswatini, and the flag of the African National Congress party in South Africa." .
