<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/d477febe81354337bb9993723f97018c> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "<STRONG>Trade beads</STRONG><BR>\nIn the 17th century, beads became an instrument in the urge for expansion of the European powers. Beads were relatively cheap and a much coveted commodity in the “newly discovered countries”. Considerable quantities of beads were exported to Africa, South-East Asia and Northern America. Important centers for bead making were in Venice, Bohemia and the Netherlands. One of the most important exporters of beads to West-Africa, intermediating between bead producers and traders, was the firm J.F. Sick & Co. <BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>J.F. Sick & Co.</STRONG><BR>\nThe company was Founded  late 1909 pr early 1910 by a Sudeten German,  J.F. Sick. The head office was first set up in Hamburg, with branches in Venice and Jablonec. After WWI, the head office was transferred to Rotterdam, and the firm name became Handelsmaatschappij N.V. v.h. J.F. Sick & Co. In 1927 the head office relocated to Amsterdam and it became an entirely Dutch company.  J.W. IJzerman (1851-1932) was the new owner. In 1959, the firm was taken over by Hagemeyer & Co. Handelmaatschappij N.V. , which until then had had its focus on the Netherlands East Indies. It was a time when the bead trade was low, due to decolonisation of the trade’s most important markets. The heydays were over, and in 1964, the Venice office was closed.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Sample card collection</STRONG><BR>\nIn that same year, the former Sick & Co. donated a unique sample collection of some 22,000 Venetian glass beads to the Tropenmuseum. The collection is an important reference of lamp beads and rosetta beads.  It consists of 197 cardboard sheets containing over one hundred beads each, and a full colour catalogue. Most of the beads date from the 1920s and 1930s. Notes on the front of the cards refer to size, colour, form or name.<BR>\n <BR>\nSource:  Brakel, Koos  van, The bead goes on: the sample card collection with trade beads from the company J.F. Sick & Co. in the Tropenmuseum, Amsterdam. Amsterdam, KIT Publishers, 2006."^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
