<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/ee1366bf75d947d5b28333565f3de14b> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "<STRONG>Combat and Weaponry</STRONG><BR>\nBefore the Dutch arrived there was no single administration for the whole of New Guinea. The island was home to small, generally isolated village communities. These rarely had a designated leader. It was only during conflicts that a man who had previously shown his ability to lead would take charge in battle. Wars were mainly between individual villages. Often these conflicts were continually recurring vendettas and were usually about territory, women and prestige. <BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Dani</STRONG><BR>\nOne of these interminable conflicts involved the Dani in the eastern central highlands. They would regularly confront each other, hundreds of men at a time, often on the same battlefield. Mutual name-calling would be followed by a rain of arrows and spears. If both sides either suffered an equal number of casualties or someone got killed, the battle would be over. A revenge attack by the defeated party could eventually lead to a new confrontation <BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Headhunting</STRONG><BR>\nA more bloody affair was headhunting. By bringing home severed heads of enemy villagers, the victims’ power would be absorbed by the headhunters’ own village. Among the Marind-anim of southern New Guinea, there was a special added purpose. They tried to get the name before killing their victim. That name would then be given to a newborn child in their own village. Entire villages would be attacked, usually just before daybreak. By killing their enemies, they avenged and placated those of their own village who had been killed, enabling life to carry on as normal. The Dutch, and later Indonesian authorities banned headhunting.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Weapons </STRONG><BR>\nMany of the objects associated with war and headhunting have been collected by ethnographic museums, and so has the Tropenmuseum: arrows, bows, spears, clubs, shields, woven cuirasses, wrist guards (to protect against the recoiling bowstring), daggers, hunting knives (razor sharp bamboo splinters), status symbols and objects for decorating the body."^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
