<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/f438bc277ee44e14bbe351033aeefe8f> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "<STRONG>In the Mentawai Islands off the west coast  of Sumatra, Indonesia, the Mentawai believe everything has a soul: plants, animals, objects and of course people themselves. The people try to respect all things around them. Shamans are asked  with performing rituals to ward off danger and preserve harmony between humans and their environment. These days, this way of life is coming under increasing pressure, however. Young Mentawai are questioning what elements of their culture they want to preserve, and why.</STRONG><BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>An old island culture</STRONG><BR>\nOn Siberut, the largest of the islands in the Mentawai archipelago, family groups still live in impressive houses (uma). Secluded in the jungle, they are virtually self-sufficient, living from hunting and fishing, pigs and chickens, and from sago and root vegetables. Goods like metal tools or outboard motors, are exchanged with outside traders. Traditional clothes are made from beaten bark and leaves, though the people also wear cotton trousers and T-shirts these days. The children are increasingly likely to go to school. Nevertheless, the Mentawai are a rare example of a culture strongly rooted in the traditions of the Stone Age.</STRONG><BR>\n<BR>\nAround 4000 years ago large parts of Indonesia were populated by immigrants from continental Southeast Asia. They used stone axes and did not grow rice in paddy fields. These were egalitarian societies. In many parts of Indonesia this culture has changed radically or even disappeared as a result of other cultural influences. In Mentawai, these later external influences were kept in check for a long time.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Seeking harmony</STRONG><BR>\nIn the traditional world view of the Mentawai harmonious relationships are key: relationships between people, and also with the natural world and with things. The focus of this belief is care for the soul. The human soul is located in the fontanel, but it moves independently of the body. Good care, rest and beautiful surroundings  ensure it remains connected to the body. Otherwise the person will die. The souls of ancestors, animals and objects also deserve respect, otherwise humans and animals fall sick, objects no longer work, and accidents happen. This pursuit of harmony is particularly strong among  the Mentawai. The warm, wet jungle is not a healthy place to live. There is a lot of disease there and child mortality is high. This might be why the pursuit of harmony plays such a big role in the traditional culture there.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>The colonial era</STRONG><BR>\n‘Noble savages’ and punitive expeditions In the late 19th century explorers, missionaries and officials of the Dutch colonial government began to explore the islands. They were impressed by the friendly, harmonious relations between the inhabitants. Their accounts are littered with words like ‘unspoilt’, ‘noble’  and ‘flower children’. They were soon being compared with Pacific islands that had been ‘discovered’ earlier, like Samoa. In the meantime, however, hostile confrontations were occurring. The Mentawai went on the occasional headhunting expedition, which the government was quick  to ban. Initially, the people refused to perform the work they were ordered to do by the Dutch. The Mentawai first killed a missionary in 1909. A number of punitive expeditions were organised in this period, and dozens of locals were killed. By 1915 colonial authority was firmly established in the coastal regions. Those living further  inland barely felt the effects of colonialism as yet.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Mentawai now</STRONG><BR>\nA lot has changed in Mentawai in recent years. In the 1970s the Indonesian government pursued an active policy of modernising the lives of the population. The traditional houses in which several families lived were mostly replaced by single family homes in villages. The traditional religion came under pressure. There are now no family houses in  the coastal regions, but there are churches and mosques. Tourists also come to Mentawai in search of authentic experiences like a jungle trek, or to surf off the coast. Groups living their traditional lifestyle are found only in the inland regions of Siberut nowadays. Many Mentawai attend school and university on the mainland, returning home as officials or teachers. Some work actively to preserve and document their culture. The highest official, the bupati, is currently a Mentawai. It will be up to these Mentawai to determine the future of the islands.<BR>\n<BR>\n<STRONG>Collecting in Mentawai</STRONG><BR>\nAs part of his fieldwork, antropologist Reimar Schefold built a large collection reflecting the material culture of Siberut. It provides a unique overview of the everyday and ritual objects made and used by the Mentawai. In abandoned family houses he found old wall panels which, like the shields and ritual objects, he exchanged for tobacco, mosquito nets, steel  and beads. Part of his collection was donated to the National Museum of World Cultures in 2017. The pieces are a well-documented addition to the objects that previous visitors brought back incidentally from Mentawai. The collection website offers an overview of the entire <a href=\"http://collectie.wereldculturen.nl/default.aspx?idx=ALL&field=*&search=mentawai\" target=\"_blank\">Mentawai collection</a>."^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
