<https://data.colonialcollections.nl/.well-known/genid/fe24337f6fa2416da38226376a360921> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P190_has_symbolic_content> "Southeast Asia has always been a crossroads in movements of people, goods, ideas and religions between West and East Asia. Europeans did not arrive there until the 16th century, seeking control of the trade in expensive spices. They gained control using force, coercion and oppression, creating mutual distrust and eventually leading to the colonisation of many countries in the region.\nIndonesia came under Dutch control, which explains the huge number of objects from Indonesia in this museum. They were sold, donated, relinquished by force or stolen. The answers to the questions of how, what and why people collected, and who they were, illustrate the relationship between Indonesia and the Netherlands.\n\nIn the 18th century, more attention was focused on the people who lived in colonised areas. With their sense of superiority, the Dutch referred to them as ‘uncivilised, wild, lazy and stupid’. Indonesians were like children who needed civilising with strict but ‘fair’ leadership. Their belief in spirits and ancestors should be replaced by Christianity. Dutch officials and missionaries banned practices they regarded as primitive and barbaric.\nFor a long time, the museum maintained a particular focus on ancestors, magic and rituals, as can be seen in this section, thus helping to perpetuate these old views." .
